## Angular Temperature Converter Tutorial

**Mental Model:** The core idea is to maintain two separate number variables for Celsius and Fahrenheit. When one input changes, we update its corresponding variable, convert that value to the other unit, and update the other variable. This ensures a two-way binding effect without direct two-way binding mechanisms.

### Step 1 — Initialize Component State
Start by defining the `celsius` and `fahrenheit` properties in your `AppComponent` class, initializing them to `null` or `undefined` to represent an empty state. We'll also add helper methods for conversion.

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <h1>Temperature Converter</h1>
    <p>Enter a value in either field to convert.</p>
    <div>
      <input type="text" [value]="celsius === null ? '' : celsius" (input)="onCelsiusChange($event)" style="margin-right: 10px; padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ccc; border-radius: 4px;">
      <label>Celsius</label>
    </div>
    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
      <input type="text" [value]="fahrenheit === null ? '' : fahrenheit" (input)="onFahrenheitChange($event)" style="margin-right: 10px; padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ccc; border-radius: 4px;">
      <label>Fahrenheit</label>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: []
})
export class AppComponent {
  celsius: number | null = null;
  fahrenheit: number | null = null;

  celsiusToFahrenheit(c: number): number {
    return (c * 9 / 5) + 32;
  }

  fahrenheitToCelsius(f: number): number {
    return (f - 32) * 5 / 9;
  }

  onCelsiusChange(event: Event): void {
    const value = (event.target as HTMLInputElement).value;
    if (value === '') {
      this.celsius = null;
      this.fahrenheit = null;
      return;
    }
    if (!/^[0-9.-]*$/.test(value)) {
      return; // Only allow numbers, period, and minus sign
    }
    const numValue = parseFloat(value);
    if (!isNaN(numValue)) {
      this.celsius = numValue;
      this.fahrenheit = parseFloat(this.celsiusToFahrenheit(numValue).toFixed(2));
    } else if (value.endsWith('.') || value.endsWith('-')) {
      this.celsius = null; // Allow partial input like '12.' or '-' without immediate error
      this.fahrenheit = null;
    }
  }

  onFahrenheitChange(event: Event): void {
    const value = (event.target as HTMLInputElement).value;
    if (value === '') {
      this.celsius = null;
      this.fahrenheit = null;
      return;
    }
    if (!/^[0-9.-]*$/.test(value)) {
      return; // Only allow numbers, period, and minus sign
    }
    const numValue = parseFloat(value);
    if (!isNaN(numValue)) {
      this.fahrenheit = numValue;
      this.celsius = parseFloat(this.fahrenheitToCelsius(numValue).toFixed(2));
    } else if (value.endsWith('.') || value.endsWith('-')) {
      this.celsius = null; // Allow partial input like '12.' or '-' without immediate error
      this.fahrenheit = null;
    }
  }
}
```

### Step 2 — Implement Input Bindings
Use `[value]` for one-way binding from the component to the input field, and `(input)` for handling changes from the input field. This avoids `ngModel` and gives explicit control over updates.

```html
<input type="text" [value]="celsius === null ? '' : celsius" (input)="onCelsiusChange($event)">
<input type="text" [value]="fahrenheit === null ? '' : fahrenheit" (input)="onFahrenheitChange($event)">
```

### Step 3 — Handle Input Changes and Conversions
Create `onCelsiusChange` and `onFahrenheitChange` methods. Inside these methods, parse the input value, perform the conversion using the helper functions, and update both `celsius` and `fahrenheit` properties. Remember to handle empty strings and invalid number inputs gracefully.

```typescript
onCelsiusChange(event: Event): void {
  const value = (event.target as HTMLInputElement).value;
  if (value === '') {
    this.celsius = null;
    this.fahrenheit = null;
    return;
  }
  if (!/^[0-9.-]*$/.test(value)) {
    return; // Basic validation for numeric input
  }
  const numValue = parseFloat(value);
  if (!isNaN(numValue)) {
    this.celsius = numValue;
    this.fahrenheit = parseFloat(this.celsiusToFahrenheit(numValue).toFixed(2));
  } else if (value.endsWith('.') || value.endsWith('-')) {
    this.celsius = null; // Allow partial input
    this.fahrenheit = null;
  }
}

// Similar logic for onFahrenheitChange
```

### Step 4 — Refine Display and Edge Cases
Ensure that when an input is empty, its corresponding bound property is `null` so the `[value]` binding correctly displays an empty string. Also, use `toFixed(2)` for converted values to limit decimal places for better readability.

```typescript
// Inside onCelsiusChange/onFahrenheitChange
if (value === '') {
  this.celsius = null;
  this.fahrenheit = null;
  return;
}

// After conversion
this.fahrenheit = parseFloat(this.celsiusToFahrenheit(numValue).toFixed(2));
```

**Edge Cases:**

| Input Type       | Expected Behavior                                  |
| :--------------- | :------------------------------------------------- |
| Empty string     | Both fields clear.                                 |
| Invalid chars    | Input is ignored, previous valid value remains.    |
| Partial numbers  | E.g., '12.' or '-' should not clear the other field immediately but allow further typing. |
| Large numbers    | Should convert correctly.                          |
| Negative numbers | Should convert correctly.                          |

**Interview tip:** Emphasize your understanding of one-way data flow (`[value]` and `(input)`) as an alternative to `ngModel` for more explicit control, and how you handle parsing and validation for user input.

